{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17629280","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17629280"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:04:56+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:04:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17265"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17265","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17265"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9955"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78050"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9955","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9955"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17265"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63472"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4945"},{"type":"tags","id":"7690"},{"type":"tags","id":"10789"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23337"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23343"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78050","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78050"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ECRISPR-Cas9 is a revolutionary gene editing technology adapted from bacterial defence systems. The system requires several components to function effectively.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the essential components required for CRISPR-Cas9 gene editing?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Guide RNA and restriction enzymes","Guide RNA and Cas9 nuclease","Cas9 protein and RNA polymerase","Reverse transcriptase and integrase","RNA polymerase and DNA ligase"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe CRISPR-Cas9 system requires two essential components: \u003Cstrong\u003Eguide RNA and Cas9 nuclease\u003C/strong\u003E. The guide RNA directs the Cas9 protein to a specific DNA sequence, where Cas9 creates a double-strand break. This enables precise gene editing through cellular repair mechanisms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERNA polymerase and DNA ligase\u003C/strong\u003E - While these enzymes are important for cellular processes, they are not the primary components of CRISPR\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECas9 protein and RNA polymerase\u003C/strong\u003E - RNA polymerase is not required for CRISPR function, and Cas9 needs guide RNA to work\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReverse transcriptase and integrase\u003C/strong\u003E - These enzymes are associated with viral genome integration, not CRISPR\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGuide RNA and restriction enzymes\u003C/strong\u003E - While restriction enzymes can cut DNA, they are not part of the CRISPR system which uses Cas9 for DNA cleavage\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter Cas9 creates a double-strand break, the cell can repair the DNA through either non-homologous end joining (which often creates small insertions or deletions) or homology-directed repair (which can introduce specific sequence changes when a repair template is provided).\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["CRISPR-Cas9 uses guide RNA to target specific DNA sequences for precise gene editing.","Double-strand DNA breaks are created by Cas9 nuclease, and can be repaired by either non-homologous end joining or homology-directed repair.","CRISPR-Cas9 requires a protospacer adjacent motif (PAM) sequence near the target site for successful binding and cleavage."],"references":["Xu Y, Li Z. CRISPR-Cas systems: Overview, innovations and applications in human disease research and gene therapy. Comput Struct Biotechnol J. 2020 Sep 8;18:2401-2415. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC7508700/","Ran F, Hsu P, Wright J, et al. Genome engineering using the CRISPR-Cas9 system. Nat Protoc. 2013;8:2281-2308. doi:10.1038/nprot.2013.143.","Redman M, King A, Watson C, King D. What is CRISPR/Cas9? Arch Dis Child Educ Pract Ed. 2016;101(4):213-215. doi:10.1136/archdischild-2016-310459."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63472"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17265"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63472","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63472"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-09T10:53:10+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-09T10:54:04+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9955"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78050"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","syno